WEBVTT

00:00:29.462 --> 00:00:30.930
Narrator:
We've long known that

00:00:30.997 --> 00:00:33.366
what happens to us in childhood

00:00:33.366 --> 00:00:36.427
can leave a lasting imprint
on the adults we become.

00:00:40.340 --> 00:00:41.671
The places we live.

00:00:42.876 --> 00:00:44.639
The people we know.

00:00:46.746 --> 00:00:48.146
The best of times...

00:00:52.118 --> 00:00:53.518
and the worst.

00:00:55.288 --> 00:00:58.485
They all somehow
become part of us.

00:01:01.261 --> 00:01:03.663
Now, a new science is telling us

00:01:03.663 --> 00:01:06.826
that our experiences go even
deeper than we thought.

00:01:08.968 --> 00:01:11.571
It happens on the genetic level.

00:01:11.571 --> 00:01:14.407
Experiences,
scientists have learned,

00:01:14.407 --> 00:01:18.078
can leave chemical marks
on our DNA.

00:01:18.078 --> 00:01:21.848
Those marks can switch
genes on or off,

00:01:21.848 --> 00:01:25.910
changing the way our bodies
and our brains function.

00:01:27.587 --> 00:01:30.490
The changes can prime us
to thrive,

00:01:30.490 --> 00:01:33.293
or they can impede development

00:01:33.293 --> 00:01:36.830
affecting health
and well-being for life.

00:01:36.830 --> 00:01:37.819
Woman:
We're talking about

00:01:37.897 --> 00:01:40.867
processes here that
are at a biological level.

00:01:40.867 --> 00:01:45.134
It just gets under the skin
in a variety of ways.

00:01:45.972 --> 00:01:47.974
Narrator:
These chemical tags are set

00:01:47.974 --> 00:01:52.378
in place during critical periods
of biological change.

00:01:52.378 --> 00:01:53.680
Woman:
There's these special

00:01:53.680 --> 00:01:56.883
vulnerabilities in utero,
during pregnancy,

00:01:56.883 --> 00:02:00.376
in infancy, in early childhood.

00:02:01.221 --> 00:02:02.288
Narrator:
Everything in

00:02:02.288 --> 00:02:06.593
an infant's experience
can help or hinder-

00:02:06.593 --> 00:02:08.288
diet...

00:02:09.028 --> 00:02:11.429
environmental toxins...

00:02:12.265 --> 00:02:14.734
housing, safety...

00:02:15.668 --> 00:02:18.433
even the parents' stress levels.

00:02:20.173 --> 00:02:21.875
These new discoveries

00:02:21.875 --> 00:02:25.145
have profound social
and political implications.

00:02:25.145 --> 00:02:29.382
Because if social influences can
alter the way our genes work,

00:02:29.382 --> 00:02:30.884
then early environments

00:02:30.884 --> 00:02:34.547
can result in biological
obstacles to success.

00:02:38.825 --> 00:02:40.793
Woman:
The poorest kids in our society,

00:02:40.793 --> 00:02:43.696
not surprisingly, are
the most vulnerable

00:02:43.696 --> 00:02:46.966
to just about every health
outcome we can measure.

00:02:46.966 --> 00:02:50.370
These are fairly healthy young
children who, with time,

00:02:50.370 --> 00:02:52.572
are going to suffer
the consequences

00:02:52.572 --> 00:02:54.631
of their social class.

00:02:55.475 --> 00:02:57.277
Narrator:
New evidence shows

00:02:57.277 --> 00:02:59.379
that social
and economic stressors

00:02:59.379 --> 00:03:02.081
can affect children in infancy,

00:03:02.081 --> 00:03:04.784
causing changes
in gene expression,

00:03:04.784 --> 00:03:07.344
changes that may last
a lifetime.

00:03:08.288 --> 00:03:09.088
Woman:
It affects

00:03:09.088 --> 00:03:10.089
their way of thinking,

00:03:10.089 --> 00:03:11.691
it affects their views
of themselves,

00:03:11.691 --> 00:03:13.352
it affects their social
relationships.

00:03:15.094 --> 00:03:16.095
Narrator:
But along with

00:03:16.095 --> 00:03:17.427
a new understanding

00:03:17.497 --> 00:03:20.733
of how early experience
influences development,

00:03:20.733 --> 00:03:23.134
this science brings hope.

00:03:24.571 --> 00:03:28.174
Improved social conditions,
the evidence shows,

00:03:28.174 --> 00:03:31.344
can actually provide
the biological foundation

00:03:31.344 --> 00:03:35.338
for lives that are healthier,
and more likely to thrive.

00:03:37.984 --> 00:03:39.952
Woman:
The science is clear about this.

00:03:40.687 --> 00:03:44.390
What we need is for the policy
to follow the science

00:03:44.390 --> 00:03:46.950
and get us to more protective
environments for children.

00:04:34.907 --> 00:04:36.509
Narrator:
Some of the first clues

00:04:36.509 --> 00:04:38.811
that our lived
experience could alter

00:04:38.811 --> 00:04:40.613
the way our genes work

00:04:40.613 --> 00:04:42.815
came from a set of experiments

00:04:42.815 --> 00:04:45.618
involving some genetically
identical mice,

00:04:45.618 --> 00:04:48.144
that somehow weren't identical.

00:04:50.256 --> 00:04:51.891
Dolinoy:
The brown pseudo Agouti mouse

00:04:51.891 --> 00:04:54.093
weighs around 27 grams.

00:04:54.093 --> 00:04:58.155
Here is the yellow mouse
that weighs around 52 grams.

00:05:00.600 --> 00:05:03.002
Narrator:
How could it be that some mice

00:05:03.002 --> 00:05:07.407
are brown and thin,
others yellow and obese,

00:05:07.407 --> 00:05:10.865
when they all share
the exact same DNA?

00:05:12.011 --> 00:05:15.982
It's what their mothers were fed
while they were pregnant.

00:05:15.982 --> 00:05:19.185
Some were fed pellets
rich in methyl groups,

00:05:19.185 --> 00:05:23.489
a molecule commonly found
in fruits and vegetables.

00:05:23.489 --> 00:05:28.394
Those mice were more likely to
give birth to brown skinny pups.

00:05:28.394 --> 00:05:31.698
But mothers fed a diet
with fewer methyl groups

00:05:31.698 --> 00:05:34.100
were more likely
to give birth to pups

00:05:34.100 --> 00:05:35.863
that were yellow and obese.

00:05:37.236 --> 00:05:39.305
Whoops! Tipped the scale.

00:05:39.305 --> 00:05:40.206
Narrator:
These studies

00:05:40.206 --> 00:05:42.809
were first conducted
at Duke University

00:05:42.809 --> 00:05:45.011
under biologist Randy Jirtle.

00:05:45.011 --> 00:05:47.980
Jirtle's team,
including Dana Dolinoy,

00:05:47.980 --> 00:05:52.748
zeroed in on one particular gene
in search of an explanation.

00:05:55.488 --> 00:05:59.092
The Agouti gene codes
for yellow fur.

00:05:59.092 --> 00:06:02.425
Curiously, it's also related
to obesity.

00:06:03.696 --> 00:06:06.399
Jirtle's team found
that the methyl groups

00:06:06.399 --> 00:06:08.101
fed to the pregnant mothers

00:06:08.101 --> 00:06:10.470
passed through to
the developing pups

00:06:10.470 --> 00:06:13.564
and attached to
their Agouti genes.

00:06:14.507 --> 00:06:17.110
It's a process called
methyl ati on.

00:06:17.110 --> 00:06:19.312
Dolinoy:
DNA methylation is the addition

00:06:19.312 --> 00:06:21.414
of a single carbon
in the form of a methyl group.

00:06:21.414 --> 00:06:23.282
So this is a carbon
and three hydrogens

00:06:23.282 --> 00:06:26.218
that sits down on DNA
and shuts genes off.

00:06:32.592 --> 00:06:34.794
Narrator:
With the gene on, or active,

00:06:34.794 --> 00:06:39.959
more mice were born
yellow and grew obese.

00:06:40.900 --> 00:06:42.602
With the gene silenced,

00:06:42.602 --> 00:06:46.163
more mice were born
brown and remained thin.

00:06:48.007 --> 00:06:51.967
Same genes,
very different results.

00:06:55.014 --> 00:06:57.244
The difference is whether
particular genes

00:06:57.316 --> 00:07:01.845
are switched on or off,
expressed or silenced.

00:07:04.090 --> 00:07:07.458
The genes we inherit
are fixed for life.

00:07:08.995 --> 00:07:11.697
But there's an entire
network of molecules

00:07:11.697 --> 00:07:14.394
that influences which
genes are expressed

00:07:14.467 --> 00:07:18.062
by making them active,
or shutting them down,

00:07:18.137 --> 00:07:21.107
like a volume control
or a dimmer switch.

00:07:21.107 --> 00:07:24.210
It's called the epigenome.

00:07:24.210 --> 00:07:25.611
Well, literally it just means

00:07:25.611 --> 00:07:27.375
"in addition to,"
or "above" the genome.

00:07:30.016 --> 00:07:31.643
Narrator:
The epigenome.

00:07:31.717 --> 00:07:33.986
It's a system
of molecular switches

00:07:33.986 --> 00:07:36.989
that interacts with our genes.

00:07:36.989 --> 00:07:38.591
Scientists are only
just beginning

00:07:38.591 --> 00:07:41.253
to understand
how it functions.

00:07:43.996 --> 00:07:48.601
Some epigenome molecules
sit literally on top of genes,

00:07:48.601 --> 00:07:51.404
fixed like barnacles
on the hull of a ship,

00:07:51.404 --> 00:07:54.669
working to switch
genes on or off.

00:07:56.609 --> 00:07:57.710
When we talk about epigenetics,

00:07:57.710 --> 00:08:00.813
we're talking a collection
of biochemical signals

00:08:00.813 --> 00:08:04.884
that control the way in
which the genome operates.

00:08:04.884 --> 00:08:07.186
We each have our own
genetic make-up.

00:08:07.186 --> 00:08:10.556
That's fixed from the time
we're conceived forever.

00:08:10.556 --> 00:08:13.549
What changes though
is the activity of genes.

00:08:15.995 --> 00:08:17.697
Narrator:
The pattern of gene activity

00:08:17.697 --> 00:08:21.601
can be absolutely critical,
even producing differences

00:08:21.601 --> 00:08:23.865
in the form and
function of cells.

00:08:25.605 --> 00:08:26.506
Meaney:
If you think about it,

00:08:26.506 --> 00:08:30.169
your body is made up of
over 200 different cell types.

00:08:30.710 --> 00:08:32.512
But they all have exactly
the same DNA.

00:08:32.512 --> 00:08:34.614
The same genes
are in your liver cell,

00:08:34.614 --> 00:08:37.344
brain cell, your muscle cells.

00:08:37.416 --> 00:08:39.485
So something has to happen

00:08:39.485 --> 00:08:42.288
to allow these cells
to become specialized

00:08:42.288 --> 00:08:44.290
to do what they're supposed
to do in your body.

00:08:44.290 --> 00:08:46.952
And that's where epigenetics
comes in.

00:08:50.096 --> 00:08:52.698
Narrator:
Epigenetic signals also turn on

00:08:52.698 --> 00:08:54.400
and off some of the genes

00:08:54.400 --> 00:08:58.104
that are constantly active
throughout our lives,

00:08:58.104 --> 00:09:04.810
like those involved in appetite,
disease-fighting, fear, focus,

00:09:04.810 --> 00:09:08.474
elation, even love.

00:09:11.817 --> 00:09:12.985
n the mice,

00:09:12.985 --> 00:09:16.489
the Agouti gene influences
not only fur color,

00:09:16.489 --> 00:09:19.592
but also body size and shape.

00:09:19.592 --> 00:09:23.696
Different epigenetic settings
result in different appetites,

00:09:23.696 --> 00:09:26.566
metabolic rates,
and fat storage.

00:09:26.566 --> 00:09:29.057
That accounts for the radically
different weights.

00:09:30.102 --> 00:09:34.807
It's a revolution in thinking
about how genes work.

00:09:34.807 --> 00:09:38.869
DNA, it turns out,
is not the master blueprint.

00:09:40.413 --> 00:09:42.214
So now you start thinking of DNA

00:09:42.214 --> 00:09:45.241
not just as an inevitable
bank of information,

00:09:45.318 --> 00:09:46.586
but you start thinking
of it as a molecule

00:09:46.586 --> 00:09:50.590
like any other molecule,
that can be more or less active.

00:09:50.590 --> 00:09:53.192
Narrator:
If gene activity is so sensitive

00:09:53.192 --> 00:09:55.394
to a naturally
occurring molecule,

00:09:55.394 --> 00:09:57.196
like a methyl group,

00:09:57.196 --> 00:10:00.600
could the synthetic substances
of our modern world

00:10:00.600 --> 00:10:03.160
be affecting the genome as well?

00:10:05.204 --> 00:10:06.939
In a follow-up experiment,

00:10:06.939 --> 00:10:11.744
Dolinoy fed her pregnant
Bisphenol A, or BPA.

00:10:11.744 --> 00:10:14.947
It's a chemical commonly
found in plastics,

00:10:14.947 --> 00:10:19.185
and associated with adverse
health effects in humans.

00:10:19.185 --> 00:10:22.188
This time, she found
less methylation,

00:10:22.188 --> 00:10:24.523
more active Agouti genes

00:10:24.523 --> 00:10:30.896
and more yellow obese pups
born to mice fed BPA.

00:10:30.896 --> 00:10:33.799
And these pups had
a host of health problems.

00:10:33.799 --> 00:10:35.301
Dolinoy:
These epigenetic changes

00:10:35.301 --> 00:10:38.464
were also correlated with
an increased risk of things

00:10:38.537 --> 00:10:40.406
like heart disease
and metabolic syndrome

00:10:40.406 --> 00:10:41.771
and obesity later in life.

00:10:43.809 --> 00:10:45.811
Narrator:
Then Dolinoy wanted to see

00:10:45.811 --> 00:10:49.315
if she could protect the mice
from the effects of BPA.

00:10:49.315 --> 00:10:52.341
So she exposed pregnant
mice to both BPA

00:10:52.418 --> 00:10:55.388
and a diet rich
in methyl groups.

00:10:55.388 --> 00:10:58.357
Again, the genome responded.

00:10:59.692 --> 00:11:03.151
The mice were born
brown and skinny.

00:11:05.064 --> 00:11:07.266
This showed,
at least in a mouse model,

00:11:07.266 --> 00:11:09.101
that nutritional interventions

00:11:09.101 --> 00:11:11.468
could counteract
the effects of toxicants.

00:11:13.406 --> 00:11:16.208
This also shows, at least
in this experiment,

00:11:16.208 --> 00:11:18.310
that theepigenome
is quite plastic

00:11:18.310 --> 00:11:20.939
and adaptable
during development.

00:11:30.089 --> 00:11:32.425
Narrator:
The idea that the epigenome,

00:11:32.425 --> 00:11:34.527
and therefore gene expression,

00:11:34.527 --> 00:11:37.263
could be modified
by environment

00:11:37.263 --> 00:11:40.099
was a radical finding.

00:11:40.099 --> 00:11:41.300
But the Agouti mice

00:11:41.300 --> 00:11:45.204
were studied under controlled
laboratory conditions.

00:11:45.204 --> 00:11:48.572
Human environments
are far more complex.

00:11:50.109 --> 00:11:54.774
A child's environment is
everything in his or her world.

00:11:55.414 --> 00:11:56.215
Woman:
Neighborhoods are

00:11:56.215 --> 00:11:57.249
defining for them.

00:11:57.249 --> 00:11:58.451
It's where they live.

00:11:58.451 --> 00:12:00.386
It's where they go
outside and play.

00:12:00.386 --> 00:12:03.289
It's where they see
their friends.

00:12:03.289 --> 00:12:06.192
The amenities, the good things,
the local park,

00:12:06.192 --> 00:12:08.794
the sidewalks that you
can ride your bike on

00:12:08.794 --> 00:12:11.997
are really wonderful
things for children.

00:12:11.997 --> 00:12:15.434
The disamenities,
things like litter

00:12:15.434 --> 00:12:19.105
and abandoned vehicles
and overgrown lots and crime,

00:12:19.105 --> 00:12:22.768
those have an equally
important effect on children.

00:12:30.516 --> 00:12:31.347
Narrator:
It's not just

00:12:31.417 --> 00:12:33.185
the physical environment.

00:12:33.185 --> 00:12:34.386
For a young child,

00:12:34.386 --> 00:12:39.154
the social and economic
environment is also key.

00:12:41.093 --> 00:12:42.925
Personal relationships...

00:12:44.063 --> 00:12:45.656
exposure to stressors...

00:12:47.233 --> 00:12:49.802
feelings of safety
or insecurity...

00:12:49.802 --> 00:12:51.668
(baby crying)

00:12:53.506 --> 00:12:56.771
all of these can get
under the skin.

00:13:00.513 --> 00:13:04.016
An adverse social environment,
the science indicates,

00:13:04.016 --> 00:13:09.648
can change a baby's epigenome
just as toxic chemicals can.

00:13:18.297 --> 00:13:20.166
In the early 1990s

00:13:20.166 --> 00:13:22.501
at McGill University
in Montreal,

00:13:22.501 --> 00:13:25.704
neurobiologist Michael Meaney
set out to understand

00:13:25.704 --> 00:13:27.973
how stressful conditions
in early life

00:13:27.973 --> 00:13:31.307
could have effects
that last a lifetime.

00:13:32.211 --> 00:13:33.212
Meany:
The first thing we wanted to do

00:13:33.212 --> 00:13:35.014
is to look at
an environmental influence

00:13:35.014 --> 00:13:37.216
that we know
has a profound effect.

00:13:37.216 --> 00:13:38.684
So we looked at maternal care.

00:13:39.785 --> 00:13:41.053
Narrator:
Meaney and his team,

00:13:41.053 --> 00:13:43.756
including then-doctoral
student Darlene Francis,

00:13:43.756 --> 00:13:45.691
observed that some adult rats

00:13:45.691 --> 00:13:47.893
seemed to be more
skittish and fearful,

00:13:47.893 --> 00:13:50.496
more stressed, than others.

00:13:50.496 --> 00:13:51.497
(thump)

00:13:51.497 --> 00:13:53.032
They went looking for factors

00:13:53.032 --> 00:13:55.034
in the rats' early
social environment

00:13:55.034 --> 00:13:57.102
that might be a clue
to the difference.

00:13:57.102 --> 00:13:59.405
Francis:
We observed hundreds of litters,

00:13:59.405 --> 00:14:01.507
hundreds of different
types of behaviors.

00:14:01.507 --> 00:14:03.909
And then when you put
all of the data together,

00:14:03.909 --> 00:14:07.179
the most powerful
predictor of stress profiles

00:14:07.179 --> 00:14:09.248
in those babies growing up

00:14:09.248 --> 00:14:11.517
was the amount
of licking and grooming

00:14:11.517 --> 00:14:12.848
they had received
from their mothers.

00:14:17.189 --> 00:14:19.391
Narrator:
Rat mothers typically lick

00:14:19.391 --> 00:14:20.893
and groom their pups.

00:14:20.893 --> 00:14:23.596
But some do it more
than others.

00:14:23.596 --> 00:14:25.965
And the difference between
high-licking mothers

00:14:25.965 --> 00:14:27.666
and low-licking mothers

00:14:27.666 --> 00:14:30.966
was reflected in their pups'
behavior as adults.

00:14:32.605 --> 00:14:34.707
The team found that rat pups

00:14:34.707 --> 00:14:36.508
that were licked
and groomed more

00:14:36.508 --> 00:14:40.212
grew up to approach the
world with greater confidence.

00:14:40.212 --> 00:14:42.014
Francis:
So these animals we put them

00:14:42.014 --> 00:14:46.285
in a little bit scary,
big empty open tub.

00:14:46.285 --> 00:14:48.487
They explore
the outer perimeter,

00:14:48.487 --> 00:14:50.089
they explore
the inner perimeter,

00:14:50.089 --> 00:14:53.354
they're doing what rats do,
which is explore.

00:14:56.495 --> 00:14:59.158
Narrator:
Not so for the low-licked rats.

00:15:01.000 --> 00:15:02.001
Francis:
Animals that were raised

00:15:02.001 --> 00:15:06.071
in low licking and grooming
environments, hug the walls,

00:15:06.071 --> 00:15:08.774
they don't explore so much.

00:15:08.774 --> 00:15:12.611
They have significantly
impaired exploration profiles

00:15:12.611 --> 00:15:13.812
or behaviors.

00:15:13.812 --> 00:15:15.178
We don't want
to stress them out.

00:15:16.515 --> 00:15:17.516
Narrator:
The low-licked pups

00:15:17.516 --> 00:15:18.617
grew up to be vigilant

00:15:18.617 --> 00:15:21.587
and hypersensitive to
noise or movement,

00:15:21.587 --> 00:15:27.355
on constant alert for threats,
even when there were none.

00:15:30.396 --> 00:15:32.598
n both rats and humans,

00:15:32.598 --> 00:15:36.502
the stress response evolved
to help us survive danger.

00:15:36.502 --> 00:15:39.438
It begins with stress hormones
like Cortisol,

00:15:39.438 --> 00:15:44.009
flooding the brain in response
to threats and challenges.

00:15:44.009 --> 00:15:47.546
A cascade of changes puts
the body on red-alert,

00:15:47.546 --> 00:15:52.985
and we're prepared to fight
or flee on a moment's notice.

00:15:52.985 --> 00:15:54.820
When the threat has passed,

00:15:54.820 --> 00:15:58.557
specialized proteins called
glucocorticoid receptors

00:15:58.557 --> 00:16:01.727
bind with the Cortisol,
neutralizing it

00:16:01.727 --> 00:16:04.958
and shutting down
the stress response.

00:16:08.200 --> 00:16:12.467
But the low-licked rats
seemed unable to calm down.

00:16:12.538 --> 00:16:15.107
Meaney's team
wanted to know why.

00:16:15.107 --> 00:16:17.943
So they looked at the regions
of the rats' brains

00:16:17.943 --> 00:16:19.968
that process stress.

00:16:21.213 --> 00:16:22.014
Woman:
So we're looking at

00:16:22.014 --> 00:16:26.246
rat brain sections, and we're
slicing hippocampus sections.

