Narrator:
When the team compared

00:16:30.789 --> 00:16:33.726
glucocorticoid receptors
in the brains of high

00:16:33.726 --> 00:16:37.396
and low-licking rats,
they had an answer.

00:16:37.396 --> 00:16:39.164
Francis:
The red represents expression

00:16:39.164 --> 00:16:41.567
of the glucocorticoid
receptor message.

00:16:41.567 --> 00:16:43.402
You can see with
the naked eye,

00:16:43.402 --> 00:16:47.206
significantly less expression
of the glucocorticoid receptor

00:16:47.206 --> 00:16:48.907
in offspring raised
in low-licking

00:16:48.907 --> 00:16:50.209
and grooming environments.

00:16:50.209 --> 00:16:54.613
And that's crucial
for dampening down

00:16:54.613 --> 00:16:56.479
further activation
of the stress response.

00:16:58.817 --> 00:17:01.587
Narrator:
Despite being genetically identical,

00:17:01.587 --> 00:17:03.889
the pups that
had been licked less

00:17:03.889 --> 00:17:07.860
had fewer glucocorticoid
receptors.

00:17:07.860 --> 00:17:09.862
With fewer receptors,

00:17:09.862 --> 00:17:12.898
their stress response
remained high.

00:17:12.898 --> 00:17:16.664
These rats stay on a fight
or flight hair trigger.

00:17:18.303 --> 00:17:20.806
Meaney turned to a second
research group

00:17:20.806 --> 00:17:25.471
to study the genes responsible
for producing these receptors.

00:17:26.512 --> 00:17:28.113
n the low-licked rats,

00:17:28.113 --> 00:17:32.151
they found that methyl groups
had attached to many genes,

00:17:32.151 --> 00:17:33.285
covering them up

00:17:33.285 --> 00:17:36.388
and preventing them
from doing their work.

00:17:36.388 --> 00:17:39.992
The genes themselves
hadn't changed.

00:17:39.992 --> 00:17:42.227
But with methyl groups
in place,

00:17:42.227 --> 00:17:46.031
the genes can't produce as
many glucocorticoid receptors

00:17:46.031 --> 00:17:49.558
and the result
is ongoing stress.

00:17:51.203 --> 00:17:53.605
This enduring physical change

00:17:53.605 --> 00:17:55.707
in the brain structure
of the rats

00:17:55.707 --> 00:17:58.710
was brought about
by purely social factors

00:17:58.710 --> 00:18:03.315
in early life-
less licking and grooming.

00:18:03.315 --> 00:18:05.651
Meaney and his colleagues
found that the changes

00:18:05.651 --> 00:18:08.787
typically last for
the lifetime of the rats.

00:18:08.787 --> 00:18:11.090
And they went far beyond
the hypervigilance

00:18:11.090 --> 00:18:12.148
he initially observed.

00:18:13.392 --> 00:18:14.693
Meaney:
You can see changes

00:18:14.693 --> 00:18:18.097
in the actual metabolic
function of the animals.

00:18:18.097 --> 00:18:20.065
For example, animals
that are licked more

00:18:20.065 --> 00:18:21.934
are less likely
to become obese.

00:18:21.934 --> 00:18:23.402
And we know that in part

00:18:23.402 --> 00:18:25.404
that's because
of the way the brain

00:18:25.404 --> 00:18:27.873
is then guiding
the endocrine systems

00:18:27.873 --> 00:18:29.541
that determine
metabolic health.

00:18:29.541 --> 00:18:31.210
So mother's licking

00:18:31.210 --> 00:18:34.146
is actually shaping
an enormous array of traits

00:18:34.146 --> 00:18:37.416
that are then
established in the pup

00:18:37.416 --> 00:18:38.884
and carried into adulthood.

00:18:40.185 --> 00:18:42.020
Narrator:
Another group of researchers

00:18:42.020 --> 00:18:44.523
wanted to know
why some rat mothers

00:18:44.523 --> 00:18:47.458
might provide less care
than others.

00:18:49.495 --> 00:18:51.964
And it turned out that
a social condition

00:18:51.964 --> 00:18:55.161
could influence
that difference as well.

00:18:57.169 --> 00:18:58.804
Francis:
We're watching this mother

00:18:58.804 --> 00:19:00.305
do the best that she can.

00:19:00.305 --> 00:19:03.108
Her stress hormone levels
are through the roof.

00:19:03.108 --> 00:19:04.977
Woman:
It's like trying to build a nest

00:19:04.977 --> 00:19:06.444
in the middle of the desert.

00:19:06.578 --> 00:19:09.172
Not the most
hospitable place.

00:19:10.816 --> 00:19:12.684
Narrator:
Rat mothers like to build nests

00:19:12.684 --> 00:19:15.387
for their pups
with soft materials.

00:19:15.387 --> 00:19:18.290
But these moms have
only been given hard,

00:19:18.290 --> 00:19:21.894
scratchy, inferior
building supplies.

00:19:21.894 --> 00:19:23.862
It's a demonstration
of an experiment

00:19:23.862 --> 00:19:26.198
first conducted by David Swett.

00:19:26.198 --> 00:19:27.399
Francis:
They really devote

00:19:27.399 --> 00:19:30.536
a lot of resources
to trying to build nests,

00:19:30.536 --> 00:19:32.704
because we took their
nesting materials away,

00:19:32.704 --> 00:19:34.104
horrible researchers
that we are.

00:19:36.408 --> 00:19:39.912
I think it's obvious that
she's trying really hard,

00:19:39.912 --> 00:19:41.213
and she's tried really hard

00:19:41.213 --> 00:19:44.979
to provide as much of a nest
as she can to her litter.

00:19:48.086 --> 00:19:49.087
Narrator:
The stressed mothers

00:19:49.087 --> 00:19:52.591
spend as much time with
their pups as unstressed moms.

00:19:52.591 --> 00:19:55.356
But they lick and groom
far less.

00:19:57.396 --> 00:20:00.899
The strain of providing
shelter with few resources

00:20:00.899 --> 00:20:05.604
impeded the rats' efforts
to care for their young.

00:20:05.604 --> 00:20:06.805
Francis:
It wasn't a time issue,

00:20:06.805 --> 00:20:08.807
but the quality of
what they were doing

00:20:08.807 --> 00:20:11.777
and how they were interacting
with their pups was different,

00:20:11.777 --> 00:20:14.213
and we were able
to identify that

00:20:14.213 --> 00:20:18.081
that directly related to
measures of the stress response.

00:20:22.387 --> 00:20:24.389
Narrator:
A stressful environment led

00:20:24.389 --> 00:20:27.192
to a low-licking mother.

00:20:27.192 --> 00:20:29.895
That low-licking mother
produced offspring

00:20:29.895 --> 00:20:33.031
that had trouble turning
their stress response off.

00:20:33.031 --> 00:20:34.600
And this triggered a cascade

00:20:34.600 --> 00:20:37.660
of health
and behavioral effects.

00:20:40.906 --> 00:20:44.409
But laboratory rats
are one thing.

00:20:44.409 --> 00:20:48.574
Would the same pattern
hold true for humans?

00:20:52.351 --> 00:20:56.855
Many American families face
an increasing load of stressors.

00:20:56.855 --> 00:20:59.291
More demands
from their employers.

00:20:59.291 --> 00:21:02.194
Less job security.

00:21:02.194 --> 00:21:03.295
Less time.

00:21:03.295 --> 00:21:05.897
Living paycheck to paycheck.

00:21:05.897 --> 00:21:07.661
Anxiety about the future.

00:21:08.700 --> 00:21:12.471
Could these growing stressors
affect not only the parents,

00:21:12.471 --> 00:21:15.873
but their children as well?

00:21:26.318 --> 00:21:30.789
In 1990, a team of researchers
at the University of Wisconsin

00:21:30.789 --> 00:21:32.991
began to measure
the stress levels

00:21:32.991 --> 00:21:36.595
in working families that
were about to have children.

00:21:36.595 --> 00:21:39.898
Some were well paid
and relatively comfortable,

00:21:39.898 --> 00:21:42.301
others less so.

00:21:42.301 --> 00:21:44.102
But the strain of coping

00:21:44.102 --> 00:21:47.105
with an increasingly
precarious middle class life

00:21:47.105 --> 00:21:50.409
was taking a toll on many.

00:21:50.409 --> 00:21:51.710
Woman:
They were stressed, you know,

00:21:51.710 --> 00:21:55.247
economically, they were stressed
by having to work two jobs,

00:21:55.247 --> 00:21:58.016
just on and on and on
with the stresses

00:21:58.016 --> 00:21:59.450
those families
were experiencing.

00:21:59.518 --> 00:22:00.285
So we turned to them

00:22:00.285 --> 00:22:02.549
to looking at the long-term
development on the children.

00:22:03.789 --> 00:22:05.290
Narrator:
Might parental stress

00:22:05.290 --> 00:22:08.851
alter the developmental paths
of their young children?

00:22:10.696 --> 00:22:13.298
Essex and her team
followed the families

00:22:13.298 --> 00:22:15.701
for more than two decades,

00:22:15.701 --> 00:22:20.238
charting stress levels,
behaviors, school performance,

00:22:20.238 --> 00:22:23.608
and other indicators
in the children.

00:22:23.608 --> 00:22:27.045
Stress was measured both
by what the families reported

00:22:27.045 --> 00:22:29.114
and by the level
of stress hormones

00:22:29.114 --> 00:22:31.276
in their blood and saliva.

00:22:34.086 --> 00:22:36.288
The results were clear -

00:22:36.288 --> 00:22:40.225
the higher a parent's stress
early in a child's life,

00:22:40.225 --> 00:22:42.594
the more stressed
the children became

00:22:42.594 --> 00:22:46.656
and the more that showed up
in their behavior later in life.

00:22:47.499 --> 00:22:48.567
Essex:
If you imagine a child

00:22:48.567 --> 00:22:50.469
that you're looking at
in a kindergarten class,

00:22:50.469 --> 00:22:54.139
it's that child that, you know,
is kind of anxious,

00:22:54.139 --> 00:22:56.007
isn't interacting
with kids very well,

00:22:56.007 --> 00:22:58.340
but is aggressive
and is impulsive.

00:22:59.311 --> 00:23:00.612
Narrator:
As the kids grew,

00:23:00.612 --> 00:23:03.181
their stress levels
remained high,

00:23:03.181 --> 00:23:05.946
even if their parents'
stress level had fallen.

00:23:07.085 --> 00:23:08.487
n adolescence,

00:23:08.487 --> 00:23:13.792
their lives still reflected
their early life experience.

00:23:13.792 --> 00:23:14.593
Essex:
They have worse

00:23:14.593 --> 00:23:15.594
peer relationships.

00:23:15.594 --> 00:23:17.262
They have more problems
with their teachers.

00:23:17.262 --> 00:23:20.298
So that is all kind of part
of the package.

00:23:20.298 --> 00:23:22.701
I mean it has very
long-term consequences

00:23:22.701 --> 00:23:24.202
that can go into adulthood.

00:23:24.202 --> 00:23:27.866
I mean the development of
substance use, teen pregnancies.

00:23:34.579 --> 00:23:35.914
Narrator:
How was it that

00:23:35.914 --> 00:23:38.383
the early experience
of their parents' stress

00:23:38.383 --> 00:23:41.649
had such a lasting impact
on the children?

00:23:44.890 --> 00:23:48.758
The answer was hiding
in their epigenome.

00:23:52.697 --> 00:23:55.600
Essex had been
collecting cheek swabs

00:23:55.600 --> 00:23:58.870
and saliva samples from
her subjects for many years

00:23:58.870 --> 00:24:01.305
so she could test
for stress hormones.

00:24:02.607 --> 00:24:05.744
A leading molecular biologist
heard about her work

00:24:05.744 --> 00:24:08.079
and realized
that those samples

00:24:08.079 --> 00:24:10.682
also contained a
treasure trove of genetic

00:24:10.682 --> 00:24:13.174
and epigenetic evidence.

00:24:15.587 --> 00:24:16.388
Man:
She had done

00:24:16.388 --> 00:24:19.858
absolutely fascinating and
groundbreaking work.

00:24:19.858 --> 00:24:22.994
And so we teamed up
and we got enough money

00:24:22.994 --> 00:24:27.299
to epigenetically profile
100 children in her cohort.

00:24:27.299 --> 00:24:28.400
What we found is that

00:24:28.400 --> 00:24:32.270
in these sixteen-year-old
kids or adolescents,

00:24:32.270 --> 00:24:35.540
their dimmer switch pattern
could be correlated

00:24:35.540 --> 00:24:40.774
to the level of maternal
stress during infancy.

00:24:42.314 --> 00:24:43.715
Narrator:
Koborhad discovered

00:24:43.715 --> 00:24:46.150
epigenetic patterns
in the teenagers

00:24:46.218 --> 00:24:48.553
that corresponded
to the amount of stress

00:24:48.553 --> 00:24:52.854
their parents had experienced
15 years earlier.

00:24:55.393 --> 00:24:57.662
This was a first -

00:24:57.662 --> 00:25:01.600
hard evidence that simply
living in a home full of stress

00:25:01.600 --> 00:25:06.204
could modify the epigenome
of infants.

00:25:06.204 --> 00:25:08.974
The second-hand stress
they experienced as infants

00:25:08.974 --> 00:25:13.070
had increased their risk for
long-term behavioral problems.

00:25:15.714 --> 00:25:18.550
The struggles of working
families in America,

00:25:18.550 --> 00:25:19.818
the study showed,

00:25:19.818 --> 00:25:23.288
had exacted a price on
the lives of their children

00:25:23.288 --> 00:25:26.519
through changed
epigenetic settings.

00:25:31.630 --> 00:25:35.967
It was an eerie replay of
the earlier study of rats.

00:25:35.967 --> 00:25:37.335
n both cases,

00:25:37.335 --> 00:25:41.172
severe and consistent
maternal stress in infancy

00:25:41.172 --> 00:25:45.410
had resulted in persistent
epigenetic changes in offspring.

00:25:45.410 --> 00:25:48.747
And the children suffered the
same host of knock-on effects

00:25:48.747 --> 00:25:51.011
as the rats.

00:25:52.417 --> 00:25:53.485
Essex:
Over a lifetime

00:25:53.485 --> 00:25:55.921
it wears and tears
on your system.

00:25:55.921 --> 00:25:58.657
You end up with association
with cardiovascular problems,

00:25:58.657 --> 00:26:00.992
with all kinds of psychiatric
problems, with obesity,

00:26:00.992 --> 00:26:04.861
and a wide range of health and
mental health kinds of problems.

00:26:09.234 --> 00:26:10.402
Narrator:
If the development

00:26:10.402 --> 00:26:12.437
of the mostly
middle class children

00:26:12.437 --> 00:26:15.168
of the Wisconsin study
can be altered...

00:26:16.308 --> 00:26:18.710
what about the millions
of American children

00:26:18.710 --> 00:26:21.975
further down the
socio-economic pyramid?

00:26:34.392 --> 00:26:36.895
In societies around the globe,

00:26:36.895 --> 00:26:39.364
researchers have found
a correlation

00:26:39.364 --> 00:26:43.101
between family wealth
and well-being.

00:26:43.101 --> 00:26:47.105
The more affluent and high
status the families, on average,

00:26:47.105 --> 00:26:50.442
the fewer adversities their
children are exposed to,

00:26:50.442 --> 00:26:52.877
and the better their outcomes.

00:26:54.312 --> 00:26:58.183
While many factors contribute
to this wealth-health gradient,

00:26:58.183 --> 00:27:00.885
the Wisconsin study
raises the question

00:27:00.885 --> 00:27:02.988
of whether epigenetic changes

00:27:02.988 --> 00:27:05.724
might occur throughout
the population

00:27:05.724 --> 00:27:07.692
on the same sliding scale

00:27:07.692 --> 00:27:12.858
that connects wealth, power
and status to well-being.

00:27:16.167 --> 00:27:19.904
The idea is unproven
but provocative.

00:27:19.904 --> 00:27:22.607
Because if social
and economic adversities

00:27:22.607 --> 00:27:24.342
