corresponding to social status,

00:27:28.613 --> 00:27:30.615
then addressing
social conditions

00:27:30.615 --> 00:27:32.982
becomes not just
a moral question,

00:27:34.185 --> 00:27:38.054
but a necessity for the success
of our society.

00:27:41.159 --> 00:27:44.162
Twenty-five percent
of U.S. children,

00:27:44.162 --> 00:27:48.690
one out of every four,
are born into poverty.

00:27:48.767 --> 00:27:51.836
They live with food
and housing insecurity

00:27:51.836 --> 00:27:54.906
and with safety concerns.

00:27:54.906 --> 00:27:58.343
They are exposed not only to
more environmental hazards,

00:27:58.343 --> 00:28:03.515
but more noise, more hardship,
more violence,

00:28:03.515 --> 00:28:07.918
and more social stressors
than their wealthier peers.

00:28:08.153 --> 00:28:09.921
And in the middle class,

00:28:09.921 --> 00:28:13.925
so many families are
increasingly pressed for time,

00:28:13.925 --> 00:28:18.263
for money,
and for resources.

00:28:18.263 --> 00:28:22.333
Could the epigenomes
of these children be modified

00:28:22.333 --> 00:28:24.903
by their social and
economic conditions

00:28:24.903 --> 00:28:28.306
just as those of the Wisconsin
children were?

00:28:28.306 --> 00:28:31.142
Are they too being
biologically primed

00:28:31.142 --> 00:28:33.475
for more difficulties in life?

00:28:36.614 --> 00:28:40.107
And if they are,
what can be done?

00:28:55.600 --> 00:28:58.503
Humans are resilient organisms

00:28:58.503 --> 00:29:02.407
and studies show that
negative epigenetic effects

00:29:02.407 --> 00:29:05.610
need not be permanent.

00:29:05.610 --> 00:29:07.312
Dolinoy:
Unlike a genetic mutation,

00:29:07.312 --> 00:29:09.371
which we can do
nothing about,

00:29:09.447 --> 00:29:11.449
an epigenetic change

00:29:11.449 --> 00:29:13.577
we may be able to
do something about.

00:29:15.386 --> 00:29:16.688
Narrator:
When Dana Dolinoy

00:29:16.688 --> 00:29:20.492
fed her pregnant yellow
obese mice an enriched diet,

00:29:20.492 --> 00:29:24.596
they gave birth to healthy,
brown slender pups.

00:29:24.596 --> 00:29:28.066
The right environment
was able to reverse the effects

00:29:28.066 --> 00:29:31.365
of a chemically induced
epigenetic change.

00:29:33.605 --> 00:29:36.174
And Michael Meaney
was able to reverse

00:29:36.174 --> 00:29:40.076
the epigenetic effects of his
nervous, low-licked rat pups.

00:29:41.513 --> 00:29:42.514
Meaney:
At the time of weaning,

00:29:42.514 --> 00:29:44.949
we put them into
enriched circumstances

00:29:44.949 --> 00:29:47.252
similar to a daycare
environment.

00:29:47.252 --> 00:29:49.988
And we then studied
these animals in adulthood

00:29:49.988 --> 00:29:50.889
and when we looked,

00:29:50.889 --> 00:29:55.349
we found that in fact, there was
a huge effect of enrichment.

00:29:56.995 --> 00:29:58.396
Narrator:
The low-licked rats

00:29:58.396 --> 00:30:01.766
in this study behaved more
like high-licked rats,

00:30:01.766 --> 00:30:03.802
exploring their surroundings

00:30:03.802 --> 00:30:07.071
with more assurance
and less fear.

00:30:07.071 --> 00:30:09.440
The enriched environment

00:30:09.440 --> 00:30:12.177
induced new changes
to the epigenome,

00:30:12.177 --> 00:30:13.611
which overcame the effects

00:30:13.611 --> 00:30:16.706
of their early epigenetic
programming.

00:30:18.416 --> 00:30:21.352
The research led to a key
new understanding

00:30:21.352 --> 00:30:23.855
of how the genome works.

00:30:23.855 --> 00:30:25.857
While genes never change,

00:30:25.857 --> 00:30:29.027
the epigenome can,
at key points in life,

00:30:29.027 --> 00:30:31.262
be remarkably plastic,

00:30:31.262 --> 00:30:33.765
adapting to individual
experiences

00:30:33.765 --> 00:30:36.257
and changing social conditions.

00:30:51.616 --> 00:30:55.787
Epigenetic changes have been
linked to adverse environments

00:30:55.787 --> 00:30:58.957
associated with
a host of ill effects -

